1. Introduction
The catalytic partial oxidation of methane (POM) to C1 oxygenates remains a challenging task with high pay-off,because of the low reactivity of the substrate and the poor selectivity to the desired products (CH3OH and/or H2CO)[17].
Many low temperature homogeneous processes in strong acidic media have been reported to convert methane to various methyl derivatives such as methanol [8,9], methane sulfonic acid [10,11], methane sulfonyl chlorides [12], methyl bisulfate [13,14], and acetic acid [1518]. But the POM over solid catalysts requires high reaction temperature and the selectivity to C1 oxygenates is poor. The target products (CH3OH and/or H2CO) are less thermodynamically stable than methane and hence are further oxidized to carbon oxides. A great deal of research has focused on many factors controlling the process activity and selectivity. Adding NOx into reactant stream of CH4/ O2 has been proved to be an efficient approach to increase the activity and selectivity of POM over silica supported vanadium oxides [1921]. Dispersion and localization state of the active phasesisanotheraffecting factor determiningthe performance of POM catalysts. The isolated active sites can prevent the over- oxidation of C1 oxygenates to carbon oxides, but the agglomerated active sites may lead to the sequent oxidation of C1 oxygenates by the vicinal sites of the reaction site [2228].
