Mesopores of MCM-41 type materials can greatly expand the capabilities of heterogeneous catalysis [34]. The capillary condensation occurs inside the mesoporous channels, allowing a relatively high concentration of reactant molecules inside the mesoporous channels. Thus, when taking the mesoporous channels as the microreactors, the reaction would proceed as if it were carried out at higher partial pressure compared with most other catalytic solid surfaces. The N2 adsorption desorption isotherm of Zn-MCM-41 exhibits a typical capillary condensation step for mesopores in the relative pressure (P/P0) range of 0.20.4 (Fig. 2). The sharpness and height of the capillary step indicate that the resulting materials have good mesopore structure ordering. A hysteresis loop is observed for the difference between desorption isotherm and adsorption isotherm cause mesopore capillary condensation. The introdu- cing of mercuric oxide leads to a marked loss of surface area.
