At 1.5 h on the reaction stream, bromine (2.0 mmol Br2) is injected into a gasification chamber and conveyed into the catalyst column by feed gas. The presence of bromine in feed gas leads to a sharp increase in the methane conversion (Fig. 3a), which demonstrates the mediator role of bromine in the methane conversion. After reaching the maximum, the methane conversion decreases gradually and fluctuates around 10%. Before introducing bromine, carbon oxides are the main products under about 2% methane conversion. With the addition of bromine, the total selectivity to C1 oxygenates (formaldehyde, methanol, and dimethyl ether) increases greatly, which reaches the maximum value of 87.6% and gradually decreases with reaction run (Fig. 3b). In all process,bromine and methyl bromide are not detected in the outlet flow of the catalyst column. The role of Zn contents in the bromine- mediated process has been established [31]. As shown by Scheme 3, the involvement of ZnO multiplies the chance of scavenging the bromine from HBr and CBr functionality to yield the oxidized products. The moderate bromine metathesis rate of ZnBr2/ZnO pairs is an important mechanism for holding bromine in the catalyst column and the promoting effects of ZnBr2 upon CH bond bromination may also reduce the leaching of unreacted bromine.
The methane oxidation over general oxide catalysts requires high reaction temperature and the selectivity to C1 oxygenates is poor. The target products (CH3OH and/or H2CO) are less thermodynamically stable than methane and hence are further oxidized to carbon oxides. But such bromine-mediated methane conversion over mercuric oxide nanophases shows relatively high selectivity to C1 oxygenates at reaction temperature of 220 8C. As revealed by Scheme 2, there are two possible reaction routes. In the cycle I, methyl bromide is first formed, and then combined with active mercuric (II) sites to give MeHgBrn, which is the precursor of C1 oxygenates. For this mechanism, the bromine concentration in the reactant flow must be kept high enough to product methyl bromide to sustain the sequent conversion. The isolated mercuric (II) cation center combined with methyl can avoid the over-oxidation of products and increase the selectivity to C1 oxygenates. In the cycle II,mercuric hypobromite formed through the insertion of bromine into zigzag OHgOHgO chains, which releases the activated lattice oxygen atoms to form Br2O, shows high activity for methane oxidation. However, the over-oxidation of target products cannot be avoided and the total selectivity to C1 oxygenates is relatively low when the methane conversion is controlled by this mechanism. As revealed by the tendency of TOS data and product distribution with reaction run (Fig. 3),both mechanisms may occur in the bromine-mediated methane conversion. In the incipient stage after bromine introducing,there is high bromine concentration in the reaction flow and the main reaction routes is the cycle I. The conversion process shows high selectivity to C1 oxygenates, as observed in Fig. 3b.
However, bromine is gradually fixed into the mercuric oxide lattice with time on stream. The controlling mechanism transfers to the cycle II and the selectivity to C1 oxygenates decreases markedly.
