Herein, it is concluded that both bromine-mediated routes described in the cycle I and the cycle II occur simultaneously in the methane conversion and the main mechanism transfers from the cycle I to the cycle II with the gradual fixation of bromine into mercuric oxide lattice.
4. Conclusion
In summary, we present a novel bromine-mediated process over supported HgO nanophases for selective methane partial oxidation at relatively low reaction temperature. A transient high product selectivity to C1 oxygenates was observed under the methane conversion of 13%, and then the methane conversion and the selectivity to C1 oxygenates gradually decrease and fluctuate around 10% and 55%, respectively. This special methane conversion was applied as the model reaction to investigate the role of bromine in the catalytic cycle. Two reaction routes can be identified: the cycle I with MeHgBrn as the intermediate species and the cycle II with mercuric hypobromite as the active agent for methane oxidation. Both bromine-mediated routes occur simultaneously in the methane conversion and the main mechanism transfers from the cycle I to the cycle II with the gradual fixation of bromine into Fig. 4. (a) XPS survey spectra of the fresh catalyst (1), the catalyst on the reaction stream of Ar/Br2 for 1.0 h (2), the catalyst on the reaction stream of Ar/CH4/O2/Br2 for 1.0 h (3), and the catalyst on the reaction stream of Ar/CH4/O2/Br2 for 3.0 h (4). (b) Br 3d XPS peaks. (c) C 1s XPS peaks.
